It&#x27;s amazing that they could have the following sentence:
&quot;Built to Spiers&#x27;s specifications, the crate allowed him to sit up straight-legged, or lie on his back with his knees bent.&quot;
and then have that graphic where his torso takes up nearly the whole 5ft length of the box.  That ridiculous graphic seems unnecessary given that that sentence explains just how he fit into the crate.

No, conflicts in LR grammars imply nothing about the ambiguity of the grammar. Only the absence of conflicts implies the grammar is unambiguous.<p>Remember that ambiguity only refers to whether or not there can be multiple derivations for the same string, <i>not</i> whether the parser action is ambiguous. For example, consider:<p><pre><code>  S: &quot;a&quot; &quot;b&quot; &quot;c&quot; | A &quot;b&quot; &quot;d&quot;
  A: &quot;a&quot;
</code></pre>
This LR(1) grammar has a shift/reduce conflict, but it is unambiguous.<p>You could even make it worse by:<p><pre><code>  S: &quot;a&quot; B &quot;c&quot; | A B &quot;d&quot;
  A: &quot;a&quot;
  B: &quot;b&quot; | B &quot;b&quot;
</code></pre>
in which interpreting this as an LR(k) grammar for all k < ∞ results in conflicts even though the grammar is still unambiguous.
